{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491031"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:28:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:28:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"809"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/809"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.06,0.03,0.01,0.79]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96694"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"809","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/809"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"809"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79323"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"538"},{"type":"tags","id":"4272"},{"type":"tags","id":"4957"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"8349"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"833"},{"type":"contributions","id":"918"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32463"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32751"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42154"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96694","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96694"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after sustaining flash burns to his face, neck and torso whilst working as a boiler maker. He has a three-hour history of progressive hoarseness and difficulty breathing. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He weighs 80 kg.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed, though is able to describe the events prior to his ED presentation. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 91% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has partial and full thickness burns to his face, neck and upper anterior chest. His facial hair, eyebrows, eyelashes and nasal hairs are singed. There is visible soot in his oropharynx and sputum. His voice is hoarse. He is becoming increasingly anxious and agitated.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management strategy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oxygen by high-flow nasal cannula and close observation","Non-invasive positive pressure ventilation","Intravenous fluid resuscitation","Intravenous corticosteroids","Endotracheal intubation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe soot deposits within the oropharynx and sputum, singed nasal hairs, and worsening hoarse voice suggests inhalation injury. The patient may have a laryngeal cord injury and is at high risk of cord oedema and complete upper airway obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe inability to produce high-pitched sounds on examination (such as a high-pitched \u0027eeee\u0027) confirms inhalational injury to the larynx. Maximal laryngeal oedema and swelling occurs at 12-18 hours post-injury, and may be delayed in the event of delayed resuscitation. Large-volume fluid resuscitation associated with the management of burn injuries may worsen cord oedema; this patient has sustained burns to approximately 12% of their body (anterior head, neck, upper torso), and will thus need 3,840ml (4ml/kg/% total body surface area) of intravenous fluid over the next 24 hours, with half delivered in the first 8 hours. There is a high likelihood of progression of his vocal cord oedema and risk of airway obstruction and therefore a planned \u003Cstrong\u003Eendotracheal intubation\u003C/strong\u003E, performed by an experienced operator, is required to protect the airway. This may occur in the emergency department, operating theatre or intensive care unit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOxygen by high-flow nasal cannula\u003C/strong\u003E and close observation would be inadequate as it does not definitively secure the airway. While high-flow oxygen can temporarily improve oxygenation (through high FiO2, humidification, and some positive pressure), it will not prevent upper airway obstruction from progressive laryngeal oedema, which is the primary concern in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-invasive positive pressure ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in this scenario. It may create a false sense of security while the upper airway continues to swell, and the mask would put pressure on facial burns, potentially worsening tissue damage. Additionally, if complete obstruction occurs, emergency intubation becomes more difficult.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fluid resuscitation\u003C/strong\u003E addresses an important aspect of care but fails to definitively secure the airway. While fluid resuscitation is necessary for burn management, this measure alone is insufficient given the high risk of complete airway obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are not the standard of care for inhalation injuries. Again, whilst they may have some benefit in reducing inflammation, intravenous corticosteroids do not provide definitive airway protection; furthermore, there is limited evidence for their efficacy in a burns setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInhalation injury is defined as damage to the respiratory tract caused by heat, smoke, or chemical irritants. Immediate injury results in erythema, oedema and ulcerations of the upper respiratory tract. It should be suspected based on clinical scenario in combination with signs such as difficulty breathing, hoarse or husky voice, singed facial hairs, burns to the face and neck or soot in the oropharynx.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that not all inhalational injury requires endotracheal intubation, and assessment should be undertaken by an experienced clinician prior to airway intervention. Clinical features may not be severe until oedema almost completely occludes the airway, and therefore the patient requires 1:1 care and monitoring regardless of need for intubation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A threatened airway after a burn injury requires prompt endotracheal intubation.","Signs of inhalation injury include singed facial hair, soot in oropharynx, and hoarse voice with inability to produce high-pitched sounds.","Maximal laryngeal oedema occurs 12-18 hours post-burn injury and may be worsened by fluid resuscitation."],"references":["Dries DJ, Endorf FW. Inhalation injury: epidemiology, pathology, treatment strategies. Scand J Trauma Resusc Emerg Med. 2013;21:31.","Walker PF, Buehner MF, Wood LA, Boyer NL, Driscoll IR, Lundy JB, et al. Diagnosis and management of inhalation injury: an updated review. Crit Care. 2015;19:351."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79323"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"809"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79323"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T16:58:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T16:59:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"809"}},"content":{"data":{"